==Recognition==
In 1988 George Juskalian was awarded the St. Nerses Shnorhali award and "Lifetime Achievement and Pastor's Recognition Award" bestowed by the [[Vasken I]], [[Catholicos of All Armenians]] for his dedication to the Armenian community.<ref name=Mirror /><ref>{{cite journal|title=Candle-lighting Marks 74th Anniversary of Washington's Armenian Community|journal=Armenian Reporter|date=November 11, 2006|volume=39|issue=7|accessdate=29 March 2013|location=Paramus, NJ|quote=Col. George Juskalian <U+2013> one of the seven recipients of the St. Nerses Shnorhali Medal among St. Mary's parishioners, bestowed by the Catholicos of All Armenians <U+2013> received a "Lifetime Achievement and Pastor's Recognition Award."}}</ref>

George Juskalian was featured in the documentary series ''[[Americans At War]]'' by the U.S. Naval Institute.<ref name=Vittori>{{cite news|last=Vittori|first=Elizabeth|title=Juskalian, Decorated Local Veteran, Honored|url=http://fairfaxstation.patch.com/articles/juskalian-decorated-local-veteran-honored|accessdate=29 March 2013|newspaper=FairfaxStation Patch|date=February 2, 2011}}</ref> Each episode of the documentary series features a U.S. veteran recounting a defining moment from his or her time in the armed services.

During a ceremony marking the 74th Anniversary of Washington's Armenian Community, Armenia's ambassador to the United States Dr. [[Tatoul Markarian]], expressed his appreciation of Col. George Juskalian's many contributions to the Armenian community, and congratulated him for his lifetime achievements.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Candle-lighting Marks 74th Anniversary of Washington's Armenian Community|journal=Armenian Reporter|date=November 11, 2006|volume=39|issue=7|accessdate=1 April 2013|location=Paramus, NJ}}</ref>

On April 23, 2007, during a formal session of the [[Fairfax County Board of Supervisors]], Juskalian was recognized for his heroism and honorable service to the United States.<ref name=Mirror />

The United States Senator of Virginia [[Jim Webb]] has stated in lieu of Juskalian's death:<ref name=Reporter />
{{quotation|It is my understanding that Colonel Juskalian was one of the most highly decorated Armenian-American Veterans to serve in the United Sates Army. I am sure his dedication to serving the Armenian-American community will be missed and his contribution will always be remembered.}}

On May 21, 2011 President [[Barack Obama]] signed House Resolution 6392 of the 2nd Session of the 111th Congress which designated the post office on 5003 Westfield Boulevard in Centreville, Virginia as the "Colonel George Juskalian Post Office Building."<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R. 6392|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/BILLS-111hr6392eh/pdf/BILLS-111hr6392eh.pdf|publisher=United States Government|accessdate=30 March 2013|date=November 29, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Statement by the Press Secretary|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2011/01/04/statement-press-secretary|publisher=The White House|accessdate=30 March 2013|location=Washington D.C.|date=January 4, 2011|quote=On Tuesday, January 04, 2011, the President signed into law: H.R. 6392, which designates a facility of the United States Postal Service as the Colonel George Juskalian Post Office Building}}</ref> The renaming ceremony of the post office took place on May 21, 2011 and was attended by friends, family, politicians, former POWs, veterans, and members of the Armenian community.<ref name=Bonnie2 /> Among the attendees included United States Congressman [[Frank Wolf]], Virginian Delegate [[Jim LeMunyon]] and member of the Fairfax County Board of Supervisors [[Michael Frey]].<ref name=Patch /><ref name=Bonnie2 /> During the ceremony, letters of appreciation sent from former Senator [[John Warner]] and Presidential candidate [[Bob Dole]] were also read.<ref name=Mirror />

